title: Scene05_Dialogue
---
Narrator: Edmund returns to the grounds of House Ashworth, but the front gate is now guarded.

Narrator: The manor that once belonged to him glows warmly beyond the iron fence. Inside, servants move as though nothing has changed.

Narrator: As though another man has not taken his place.

Narrator: Edmund keeps to the shadows and circles toward the old servant passage behind the west garden.

Narrator: The passage door is rusted shut.

Edmund: Still here.

Edmund: Father always said this door was older than the house itself.

Narrator: He kneels beside the lock and brushes away the dirt.

Edmund: And still as stubborn.

Narrator: The old lock gives away after a hard pull. The servant passage opens with a low groan.

Narrator: Edmund hastily slips inside.

Narrator: After a while, he reaches his father's old workshop.

Narrator: Workbenches line the wall. Shelves sag under broken parts — gears, springs, scraps of tarnished gold. A cracked wall clock hangs above the room, its face blackened by old smoke, hands hang loose beneath the glass.

Narrator: The room smells of dust, old wood, and extinguished candles.

Edmund: Father's workshop... No one has used this place in years.

Edmund: The West Wing clock.

Edmund: Father brought it here after the fire.

Edmund: He never rewound it.

Narrator: Beneath the clock face, set into the wooden base, are two small brass controls — one marked HOUR, one marked MINUTE.

Edmund: He used to say a dead clock should remember the hour it died.

Narrator: Edmund draws out the medical record from his coat and looks at the recorded time.

Edmund: 2:15 A.M.

Edmund: The hour the West Wing burned.

Narrator: He grips the brass controls.

Edmund: Then remember.

Narrator: A hidden compartment opens beneath the clock.

Narrator: Inside, wrapped in an old handkerchief marked with the crest of House Ashworth, lies a small damaged gold gear.

Edmund: I hid this myself. Inside the dead clock.

Edmund: No servant knew. No tutor knew. Not even Father.

Narrator: He holds the broken gear tightly.

Edmund: A face can be copied. A voice, imitated.

Edmund: But no one knew this clock opened. No one knew this gear existed.

Edmund: No one should have.

Other Him: You remember that too?

Edmund: How do you know this clock?

Other Him: The same way you do.

Edmund: You are a thief.

Other Him: Perhaps.

Edmund: You stole my house. My name. My life.

Other Him: Then take them back at the Trial.

Edmund: Why are you doing this?

Narrator: The opposing man looks at the broken gold gear in Edmund’s hand. Something passes across his face — not envy. Something closer to relief.

Other Him: Because one of us must be believed.

Edmund: And you expect it to be you?

Other Him: No.

Other Him: Bring that gear to the Trial.

Edmund: Wait.

Edmund: “You remember that too.”

Edmund: Not “how did you open it.” Not “what is that.”

Edmund: Too.

Narrator: He looks down at the gear. For the first time, he is not certain the memory is his alone.

Narrator: The second proof has been found.

Narrator: Memory Proof.

===
